## Current Issues

### 1. 🔒 Missing Input Parsing Middleware
The app has no body parser configured. Any `POST`/`PUT` route added later would silently fail or be vulnerable to large payload attacks.

### 2. 🛡️ No Rate Limiting
The `/users` endpoint (and all others) have no rate limiting, making the server vulnerable to brute-force and DoS attacks.

### 3. ❌ No Global Error Handler
Unhandled errors will cause Express to leak stack traces to the client, revealing implementation details.

### 4. 📋 No Request Logging / Audit Trail
There's no access logging, making it impossible to detect or investigate suspicious activity.

### 5. 🔓 Missing Security Headers
No HTTP security headers (e.g., `X-Content-Type-Options`, `X-Frame-Options`) are set.

### 6. ⚠️ No 404 Handler
Unknown routes return Express's default HTML error page, which leaks framework info.

---

## Suggested Improvements

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
const helmet = require('helmet');

const app = express();

// ── Security headers (helmet sets X-Content-Type-Options, X-Frame-Options, etc.)
app.use(helmet());

// ── Body parsing with size limit to prevent payload-based DoS
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true, limit: '10kb' }));

// ── Rate limiting: max 100 requests per 15 min per IP
const limiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000,
  max: 100,
  standardHeaders: true,   // Return RateLimit-* headers
  legacyHeaders: false,
  message: { error: 'Too many requests, please try again later.' },
});
app.use(limiter);

// ── Simple request logging (replace with a proper logger like `morgan` in prod)
app.use((req, _res, next) => {
  console.log(`[${new Date().toISOString()}] ${req.method} ${req.path}`);
  next();
});

// ── Health check
